  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Established global standards for combating money laundering\n- Provides guidelines for financial institutions and governments\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Provide frameworks for preventing financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision standards\n- Sets regulations for banking practices to prevent money laundering\n\n5. Individual countries have their own specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Many countries require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\nThese laws typically require:\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting of suspicious activities\n- Cooperation between international law enforcement agencies\n\nMost developed countries have implemented comprehensive anti-money laundering regulations to prevent financial crimes and track potential illegal activities.",
